          "body": "The theological center of the chapter is the most remarkable passage in Judges. When Israel cries out, the LORD does not send a deliverer. He delivers a speech. He recites His own history of rescue — Egypt, Amorites, Ammon, Philistines, Sidonians, Amalekites, Maonites — seven deliverances to match the seven sets of gods Israel is currently serving. The argument is covenantal: the track record of rescue was not earned by Israel's merit but given by Yahweh's faithfulness; Israel has responded by abandoning the Rescuer for gods with no rescue history at all. The command in 10:14 — 'go and cry out to the gods which you have chosen; let them deliver you' — is not cruelty but ontological exposure. Idols cannot deliver because they are not real. The challenge forces Israel to face what they have actually chosen, not what they imagined they were choosing. Calvin notes that God often withdraws His hand precisely to make us feel the void that our idols create (Commentary on Judges). The speech is the most merciful possible preparation for the repentance that follows."
