          "body": "The most theologically striking clause in the chapter is the last clause of verse 16: 'and He could bear the misery of Israel no longer.' The Hebrew attributes this to Yahweh's nephesh — His soul, His self. The verb qatser means to be short, to be pressed, to be unable to contain. Yahweh's soul was pressed short by Israel's suffering; His grief at their misery overcame the judicial withdrawal He had announced. This is not a contradiction of divine impassibility in the classical sense — it is the language the author deploys to insist that Yahweh is not a detached cosmic administrator but a grieving covenant Lord who is genuinely moved by the suffering of His people even when that suffering is the direct consequence of their own sin. Jonathan Edwards noted that divine love is the deepest motivation behind divine displeasure: God's anger at Israel's idolatry and God's grief at Israel's misery are not in competition — they are two expressions of the same love (Religious Affections). Judges 10:16 gives us a God who cannot be reduced to mechanical judgment any more than He can be reduced to automatic rescue."
