        "excerpt": "Then the sons of Israel again did evil in the sight of the LORD, served the Baals and the Ashtaroth, the gods of Aram, the gods of Sidon, the gods of Moab, the gods of the sons of Ammon, and the gods of the Philistines.",
        "body": "The apostasy notice of verse 6 is the longest and most geographically comprehensive in the book. Where previous cycles named one or two competing deities, this cycle names seven categories: Baals, Ashtaroth, and the gods of five surrounding nations. The number seven in Hebrew narrative often signals totality or completeness — Israel's idolatry here is total. They have worshipped every available alternative to Yahweh. The symmetry with Yahweh's speech in 10:11-12 is deliberate: He will enumerate seven past deliverances to match Israel's seven-fold defection.\n\nThe theological force of listing the nations alongside their gods is important. Aram, Sidon, Moab, Ammon, and Philistia were Israel's neighbors and frequent treaty partners. Their gods came packaged with their political relationships. The narrator is showing that Israel's covenant failure is simultaneously a failure of political separation — they have not merely borrowed worship practices; they have absorbed the cosmological frameworks of every nation around them. The avad (service/worship) they render to these gods is the same word used of their covenant obligation to Yahweh: they have given their full covenant fealty to every nation's deity except their own.\n\nYahweh's response — selling Israel into the hands of the Philistines AND the Ammonites simultaneously (10:7) — is proportionate to the breadth of the sin. Prior judgments came through a single oppressing nation; this judgment is dual. The affliction is physical ('crushed,' *ratsats*, a word meaning to shatter or grind) and extended (eighteen years, 10:8). The Ammonites then cross the Jordan and press into Judah, Benjamin, and Ephraim (10:9) — the crisis moves inward from the frontier toward the tribal heartland. The geographic expansion of oppression mirrors the breadth of Israel's idolatrous expansion.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Aph charah* (his anger burned, 10:7) — literally 'his nostril grew hot,' the idiom of Yahweh's judicial wrath being activated. *Makhar* (He sold them, 10:7) — the same commercial verb used in 2:14 and 3:8; Israel is treated as property transferred to a new owner. *Ratsats* (crushed, 10:8) — to shatter, to grind underfoot; used elsewhere of crushing oppression (Isaiah 58:6; Amos 4:1). The severity of the verb matches the severity of the apostasy."
