        "body": "The divine refusal speech of verses 11-14 is without parallel in the book of Judges. At every prior cycle, Israel's cry produced a deliverer — the cycle's automatic rescue mechanism seemed reliable. Here Yahweh interrupts the pattern with a prosecutorial speech that recites seven past deliverances and then declares the pattern broken. The rhetorical structure is a covenant lawsuit (*rib*): historical recitation of Yahweh's faithfulness (10:11-12), the indictment of Israel's forsaking (10:13a), the announced judgment (10:13b), and the challenge to test the alternative (10:14).\n\nThe irony of verse 14 is surgical. 'Go and cry out to the gods which you have chosen' is not cruelty — it is the most efficient route to Israel's recovery of theological reality. The gods they have chosen are functionally null. They have no track record of delivering from Egypt, Amorites, Ammon, Philistines, Sidonians, Amalekites, or Maonites. Yahweh's seven-fold rescue history has no counterpart in any Canaanite or Aramean deity's record. The command to cry to the idols is a pedagogy of absence: let Israel discover what they have actually chosen before they come back to the One who actually delivers.\n\nOrthodox Reformed commentators (Calvin, Matthew Henry) read this speech as the covenant lawsuit form of Leviticus 26 and Deuteronomy 32 — the 'Song of Moses' pattern where Yahweh's historical faithfulness is contrasted with Israel's defection, and withdrawal of rescue is the named consequence. It is not divine capriciousness but covenant faithfulness operating in its negative register: the same God who binds Himself to deliver a faithful people binds Himself to withdraw from an apostate one. The speech is theologically serious precisely because Yahweh means it — and Israel must reckon with the fact that He means it before genuine repentance becomes possible.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Azav* (forsaken, 10:13) — to leave behind, to abandon. The same root used of leaving a sick or dying person, or of abandoning a post. *Yasah* (save/deliver) appears three times in 10:12-14 — the historical deliverances and then the ironic command to let the idols 'save.' The repetition is deliberate mockery of the idols' impotence. *Batstsarah* (distress, 10:14) — the same word used in 10:9 for Israel's distress under oppression; Yahweh uses their own vocabulary back at them."
